Terminal and test execution policy for this repository:

- For any test, build, UI automation, 1C launch, or long-running command, use only:
  .\scripts\test.ps1

- Never run these commands directly for test/build/debug workflows:
  pytest
  python -m pytest
  pdm run pytest
  pdm run -p .dev pytest
  1cv8
  1cv8c
  powershell with inline automation logic
  cmd /c for test orchestration
  any infinite retry loop in terminal

- Allowed direct terminal commands are limited to safe read-only inspection commands such as:
  git status
  git diff
  git log --oneline -n 20
  rg
  Get-Content
  ls
  dir

- Before changing scripts/test.ps1, explain why the change is needed.

- scripts/test.ps1 is a deterministic command runner with strict scope:
  - runs a command in an isolated PowerShell process
  - captures stdout/stderr into log files
  - enforces a timeout
  - on timeout, terminates ONLY the child process tree (taskkill /T)

- scripts/test.ps1 MUST NOT perform any global process cleanup:
  - do NOT kill processes by name (python, node, 1cv8, etc.)
  - do NOT scan the system for "similar" processes (e.g. pytest)
  - do NOT use command-line pattern matching to kill processes
  - do NOT attempt heuristic cleanup outside the process tree

- Only processes started by the wrapper are allowed to be managed.

- If some process survives after timeout, treat it as a bug in process spawning,
  NOT as a reason to introduce broader cleanup logic.

- When tests are needed, invoke the wrapper script and pass the target test command through its parameters.

- After each wrapper run:
  1) inspect exit code,
  2) inspect the produced log,
  3) only then decide next steps.

- Do not start a new test run if the previous wrapper run reported timeout, cleanup failure, or a still-running child process.

- Do not spawn background processes unless explicitly requested.

- Do not create endless “run until green” terminal loops. Instead:
  1) run wrapper once,
  2) inspect failure,
  3) change code,
  4) run wrapper again.

- Any 1C-related run must also go through the wrapper script so that process lifecycle is controlled ONLY via the wrapper.

- If a direct command would violate this policy, stop and use .\scripts\test.ps1 instead.